Lately…

If you know me, you know how much I lurv the country of my beginnings. Join me, @mosito.ramaili @lihle_z @nolitazita @msrobynjade_ @aqbeglobal and the entire @saffasinnyc crew for a celebration of SA culture in BK. 

:::::::::::::::::::::

🎉SAFFAS IN NYC in partnership with @brandsouthafrica & @globalrsa_ invite you to join us for an electrifying celebration of South African Youth Day! 🇿🇦✨

LINK IN BIO TO RSVP!!!!! 

🗓️ Mark your calendars for Sunday, June 25th from 1pm to 5pm as we commemorate the power and potential of our incredible youth! 

🎤 Get ready for mesmerizing performances, thought-provoking panel discussions, and infectious beats by the one and only DJ AQ. 🎧🎶

🌟 Immerse yourself in a dynamic atmosphere filled with inspiration, music, and shared experiences. Together, we’ll celebrate the achievements and aspirations of our youth.

🌭🥤 Delicious food will be provided, so come hungry and ready to indulge!

📍 Venue: SEED BRKLYN
1217 Bedford Avenue, Brooklyn 

📣 Don’t miss out on this unforgettable occasion where unity, talent, and the spirit of the youth will shine! Join us and be part of the movement. 🙌

#YouthDayCelebration #SouthAfricanYouth #EmpoweringTheFuture #MusicAndInspiration #DJAQ #BYOB #CommunityEvent

Life lately…

Inspired by the Janelle’s #ageofpleasure and calling for a “summer of pleasure.” 

Pleasure is everywhere… if you’re looking. Pleasure is the joy of seeing our sis @apshantology open @beaucouphoodoo, a African-centered bookstore and botanica in Germantown, Philadelphia. We celebrated!

Pleasure lives in friendships, in community. Pleasure lives in beauty, like the feast for the eyes that is the #africafashion exhibition at @brooklynmuseum. 

Pleasure loading… 🤍

On beauty. Who gets to have it; who doesn’t? To my younger self I always give gratitude. She was bold and used the space afforded by societal messages of not being deemed desirable to cultivate an inner life. Even in my 40’s I honor her audacity. She is my beauty. 

Now roll the clips…🤣
1. 📹 @candicebrathwaite speaking faxxxx via @girlswillbeboys_ 

2. I remember watching The Oprah Winfrey Show way back and hearing Maya Angelou speak on beauty and a lightbulb going off. She said, “I decided a long time ago that I would not be pretty… so I thought I’d better be BRILLIANT.”

3. You better sang #JanisIan. “It was long ago and far away/ The world was younger than today/ When dreams were all they gave for free/ To ugly duckling girls like me.”

4. A word from @jasmineelliscomedy: “As long as a woman knows how she is perceived, someone—well-meaning or not—will tell her she is wrong.” Whew!

🪩 She summoned us to the Renaissance. We came in all hues, shapes and sizes, rocking sequins, rhinestone and anything extra AF. The frequency was YASS!! and love and joy reigned supreme.

My take is there are three phases to the #renaissanceworldtour experience:

1. There’s the before concert cuteness. We’re all doing photo shoots outside the venue and screaming yasssss to strangers. It’s a vibe. My wig Kiki and I partook in the festivities. 

2. Now you’re at your seat and the WORKOUT is about to begin! You’re singing along to every note and essentially doing cardio because the dancing is so intense. Beyoncé does give you a few water breaks between workouts tho. 💦

3. Okay, now comes the raggedy part. The concert is done and it was one thousand percent an incredible experience. But you’re entering your  disheveled phase. You’re making your way out of the stadium sweaty and your feet will not let you be great. 

In short, stretch before you go. 

Jokes aside! That was brilliant. Beyoncé is certainly among the greats when it comes to live performance and visual storytelling. 🐐To me, B and her creative/research team are archivists, meticulously documenting and celebrating Black creative expression. That was dope. 10/10 @yvettenoelschure 🪩

TikTok vid credit: @ african_millennialz

Always assume hoodrat!” @browngirlbooklover posted this a while ago and it’s been on my mind ever since. The bookish, nerdy, spiritual, alternative AND hood coexistence is my fave. You can’t touch us! Beloved. 

Badu once said “This tea and incense can turn into colt 45 and Newports” real quick.

I’ve just had the most incredible two days at the @fnbartjoburg, Africa’s biggest contemporary art fair. Johannesburg, you owe me nothing!! From the art to the fashion to the beautiful and familiar faces, I couldn’t be more grateful. Thanks for extending an invitation to experience the best in African art @visitsouthafrica. 

Truly, nothing beats the warmth of the African sun ☀️

Getting back home to South Africa in September will also hold a special place in my heart. It’s the month both of my parents transitioned to the ancestral plane. Getting to touch African soil and lay flowers on their graves will always be special. This visit was electrifying. My God. The vibration was elation; the attitude was gratitude. My heart is so full. South Africa, your love is 👑, truly elite. I return to NYC feeling renewed. 

For this trip home, I was lucky enough to briefly #visitsouthafrica like a tourist would. We traveled the vibrant streets of Soweto, danced the night away at @artivistjhb where I immediately became a DJ @mamthug stan, saw #NelsonMandela’s personal archives up close (gasp!), spent a morning at @nelsonmakamo’s art studio, walked through Braamfontein to see the street art, and got to bump into fellow Brooklynite @mtkalla in the streets of Jozi. How dope!

And then there was picturesque Cape Town where we got to visit so many Black-owned spaces and makers, like @klein_goederust, the only Black-owned wine farm in The Franschoek wine valley. We ate, “experienced” South African wine culture (lordy, Saffas love their wine), and clink clinked 🥂like nobody’s business. But mostly, we laughed and had so many special moments. 

I could go on and on. Ndiyabulela 🙏🏾

Me: Why does your generation cover your faces when you take photos? 👀

Also me: But why do you look down? Blank stare and I proceed to STFU 🫠

Where has the time gone? Happy birthday firstborn love of our lives, Melisizwe @mellyfrm4 with the big name. You are loved. 

📸 @swaggstar4k

There are few moments in my professional life that bring me more pride than getting to be Executive Producer of NPR’s #Throughline podcast and working with Rund Abdelfatah, Ramtin Arablouei (@ibn_nader), @jtexasc, and so many more. 

Imagine me, a history buff, getting to work on a history podcast?! The stars were truly aligned. Rund and Ramtin’s rigor and storytelling style  is to be admired. We even won a #PeabodyAward last year!

This is just a dedication post to the dopest team that I got to work with for 2.5 years, and also a recommendation for you to dive deep into #ThroughlineNPR🎧. Also, support public media @npr.

Recently, “Water” singer Tyla declared that she was Coloured not Black causing quite a stir on these shores. But also opening up dialogue about how Blackness is classified and experienced outside of America. See clips. 

This Sunday at the newly opened @babelloft, join me for a discussion of the multifaceted identity and rich cultural heritage of Coloured people in South Africa with @tessa.dooms who recently co-authored “Coloured: How Classification Became Culture” with @lynseychutel. We’ll be joined by @jodyfjacobs. RSVP link in bio.

We had a fascinating conversation on the identity and culture of the Coloured people of South Africa. I was floored (literally mouth agape) to learn how little I truly knew about Coloured people and culture. Of course this was by design, because if there’s anything the Apartheid government mastered, it was Divide and Conquer. 

Thanking @tessa.dooms and @lynseychutel for bringing this important conversation on Coloured identity to the forefront through their book “Coloured: How Classification Became Culture.” It’s available to order. Thank you @babelloft and @sasyrae for having us. Thank you @jodyfjacobs for your brilliance and insights. And to all who joined us on a rainy day🙏🏾🙏🏾

On being politically Black and culturally Coloured - @tessa.dooms
 📹 @m_square @lihle_z

Death is a thief. 
Ok, maybe that is too harsh. 
So how to describe how death slams doors you thought would be open forever? Or just a little longer. 
For one more long, meandering phone call. 
Just one more laugh with one of the funniest elder you knew. Just one more story from her. 

My aunt Sheila has joined the ancestral plane. Mrs. Paris. The most glamorous of the women who raised me. The most daring. The most fearless. She was the one you sent in when you wanted to get shit done. Voice, booming. Audacity on 1000+ 

The enforcer, the agitator, the glamour puss, the creative, the globe hopper, the storyteller. The beloved. All in one. Ugh 💔

“If I must die, you must live, to tell my story…” #refaatalareer 

Most of my time here is spent listening. To nature, to the people, to the songs. The songs! 🤍

Sheila, world traveler, wanted to buried where her life began, Palmerton, Lusikisiki, deep in valleys of the Eastern Cape. We came to celebrate a life well-lived. We laughed, we danced, and admired the beauty around us. And then, hours later, we heard news of the tragic passing of another giant we had just been dancing with hours earlier at Sheila’s homegoing. #mbongeningema Life, wena 💔
